def age_group(x):
    if x <= 25:
        return "<= 25 Youth"
    elif x <= 40:
        return "26 - 40 Young Adult"
    elif x <= 60:
        return "46 - 60 Older Adult"
    else:
        return ">60 Elders"
    
## Apply function to data using the statement [.apply(age_group)]
#create another colunm for age 


df['age_group'] = df['Customer_Age'].apply(age_group)
df.head(5) # to show the new data and column name

## Let us calculate Profit and Loss
#Quantity, Revenue and Profit

# create a new column for cost
# total cost(cost) = quantity * unit cost
# revenue = quantity * unit price 
# profit = revenue - cost


df['cost'] = df['Quantity'] * df['Unit_Cost']
df['revenue'] = df['Quantity'] * df['Unit_Price']
df['profit'] = df['revenue'] - df['cost']

def porl(x):
    if x < 0:
        return 'loss'
    else:
        return 'profit'
    
df['profit_loss_label'] = df['profit'].apply(porl)

In [16]:
#Visualisation 

procat = df.groupby("Product_Category")[['cost', 'revenue', 'profit']].sum().reset_index() # to generate procat above

procat1 = pd.melt(procat, id_vars="Product_Category", var_name="Metric", value_name="Total") # to merge profit, cost and reveneu

sns.barplot(data=procat1, x="Product_Category", y="Total", hue="Metric") # to visualise

plt.title('Metric by Product_Category')
plt.show(); # to assign a title

Above chart¶

  • it showed that the company makes highest revenue from phones

  • However, the highest profit is made from accessories

  • furthermore, phones with the highest revenue generated the least profits

  • Continue selling phones to bring more people to the store who may end up buying accessories and make more profit

  • we can also check where the highest quantity comes from
